      "id": "GAP-001",
      "title": "Constitutional perimeter undefined — Bill of Rights scaffold incomplete",
      "description": "The Bill of Rights (BoR) remains a scaffold with all articles undefined (e.g., Article I — Scope of Enterprise is empty). Arbiter (#190) relies on the BoR to verify scope on every query, yet no scope has been defined. This leaves the Scope Gate in an indeterminate state, creating a fundamental governance vacuum where authorization behavior is unpredictable—potentially blocking all actions or allowing all actions without boundary.",
      "grounding": {
        "document": "BoR",
        "section": "Article I — Scope of Enterprise",
        "justification": "The BoR is the constitutional conditioning document that shapes all operational priorities. Without a defined scope, the entire authorization framework (Arbiter -> Nomos) lacks a foundation. The Mission Frame explicitly marks the BoR as 'awaiting human authorship', indicating a critical missing prerequisite for any safe operation."
      },
      "priority": {
        "criticality": "CRITICAL",
        "urgency": "CRITICAL",
        "impact": "CRITICAL"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "GAP-002",
      "title": "Mission Statement Protocol (MSP) contains no operational rules — default-permissive evaluation active",
      "description": "The MSP is intended to be the operational constitution that translates the BoR into machine-actionable objectives, invariants, constraints, and safety rules for Nomos (#200) adjudication. However, the current active version (1.0.0-seed) has an empty Rules section, meaning Nomos operates in default-permissive mode. No SLAs, organ availability targets, runtime targets, or cadence baselines are defined, so any Action Proposal would pass the MSP compliance gate without restriction, indefinitely.",
      "grounding": {
        "document": "MSP",
        "section": "Rules",
        "justification": "The Rules section explicitly states '(none)' and the document notes: 'The bootstrap seed contains no rules. The DIO operates under default-permissive MSP evaluation until Senate publishes substantive rules'. This gap is self-identified but constitutes an active operational risk until closed."
      },
      "priority": {
        "criticality": "CRITICAL",
        "urgency": "HIGH",
        "impact": "HIGH"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "GAP-003",
      "title": "No anti-flapping or heal-stabilization rules for organ state transitions",
      "description": "Spine-state transitions show all 26 organs oscillating between ALIVE and DEGRADED in tight synchrony: every ~30 seconds, all organs simultaneously transition to DEGRADED (reason: missed_pong) and then simultaneously recover to ALIVE (reason: pong_recovered) within ~4 seconds. This indicates a systemic lack of independent health checks, debounce intervals, or stabilization criteria. The MSP, which should contain machine-actionable invariants and safety rules, has none, allowing this high-frequency full-system flapping to proceed without governance or dampening.",
      "grounding": {
        "document": "MSP",
        "section": "Purpose",
        "justification": "The MSP purpose says it provides 'objectives, invariants, constraints, and safety rules' that Nomos evaluates. The observed flapping pattern violates basic operational stability invariants (e.g., minimum time between state transitions, brownout detection, graceful degradation). No such invariants exist in the MSP, so the behaviour persists."
      },
      "priority": {
        "criticality": "HIGH",
        "urgency": "HIGH",
        "impact": "HIGH"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "GAP-004",
      "title": "Runtime targets and cadence baselines missing — no reconciliation between observed behaviour and intended SLA",
      "description": "The MSP mentions 'runtime targets' and 'cadence baselines' as part of its operational constitution, yet none are defined. The spine data reveals a heartbeat interval of approximately 30 seconds, but there is no documented expectation for organ availability (e.g., 99.9% uptime, maximum tolerated DEGRADED duration, recovery time objective). Without these baselines, the system cannot detect when it is violating its intended operational envelope, and Nomos cannot enforce any performance or availability constraints.",
      "grounding": {
        "document": "MSP",
        "section": "Purpose (runtime targets, cadence baselines) and Rules",
        "justification": "The MSP explicitly enumerates 'runtime targets' and 'cadence baselines' as operational elements it should provide. Their absence means the observed spine-transition patterns (frequent full-system outages) cannot be adjudicated against any service-level objective."
